                <td bgcolor="#37437B" valign="top"
 nowrap><b><font color="white" face="trebuchet ms,tahoma" size="2">Sthythys</font></b></td>
                <td bgcolor="#37437B" valign="top"><font color="white" face="trebuchet ms,tahoma" size="2"><small>Posted&nbsp;-&nbsp;12/18/2003&nbsp;: 07:47:37 AM</small><hr size="1"><span class="spnMessageText"> Rather than using shock of poison and fire dot, I would load root and undead-nuke.  <br /><br />Why not shock of poison?  The dmg is less but the DPM is about the same...BUT, you should find it less resisted (it's not a true rule but undeads do often tend to have high PR) and it help you get skillups in Evocation, a skill many of us forget to practice at the lower levels since we have so few spells that use it.<br /><br />And as for charming, you may not be used to it from playing a mage (no root spells) but when you are charming solo you ALWAYS want to have root loaded if you can...for when charm breaks so you only have one mob coming at you...and also for CC.  Screaming Terror, because of its short duration, can only be used effectively on two mobs at a time (assuming none of them are DoT'd).  Consider root an additional CC spell that you can use to control several mobs all at once.<br /><br />Root is also a great spell for pulling mobs when you cannot feign (like when you are charming).  Root one mob and his buddy comes...deal with his buddy then go after the rooted guy.  Using a combination of ST and root (actually both lines of root--the fast cast and the long duration) allowed me to deal with 6-7 mobs at a time charming in ME when hunting for my VT shard from there..that's one of the most satisfying times I've had, hunting, was having a monster of a charmed pet killing one rooted mob, two mobs mez'd, and 3 or 4 mobs rooted waiting to die to my pet...it's exciting AND impresses the hell out of onlookers who are used to pansy-nec's who FD or run to zone when they get an add :)</span></font></td>
